nguage-text\">Err</code>","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":468,"offset":1017},"end":{"line":8,"column":473,"offset":1022},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" and ","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":473,"offset":1022},"end":{"line":8,"column":478,"offset":1027},"indent":[]}},{"type":"html","value":"<code class=\"language-text\">orf</code>","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":478,"offset":1027},"end":{"line":8,"column":483,"offset":1032},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" to find offsets where an ","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":483,"offset":1032},"end":{"line":8,"column":509,"offset":1058},"indent":[]}},{"type":"html","value":"<code class=\"language-text\">Err</code>","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":509,"offset":1058},"end":{"line":8,"column":514,"offset":1063},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" trigram is found three characters before an ","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":514,"offset":1063},"end":{"line":8,"column":559,"offset":1108},"indent":[]}},{"type":"html","value":"<code class=\"language-text\">orf</code>","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":559,"offset":1108},"end":{"line":8,"column":564,"offset":1113},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" trigram. The locations and lengths of these postings lists on disk are kept in RAM, along with various other metadata, to make searches go faster. Determining that a repo has ","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":564,"offset":1113},"end":{"line":8,"column":740,"offset":1289},"indent":[]}},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"no","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":741,"offset":1290},"end":{"line":8,"column":743,"offset":1292},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":740,"offset":1289},"end":{"line":8,"column":744,"offset":1293},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" instances of a trigram that is required by the input lets the entire repository be skipped.","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":744,"offset":1293},"end":{"line":8,"column":836,"offset":1385},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1,"offset":550},"end":{"line":8,"column":836,"offset":1385},"indent":[]}},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"In the below image, the large purple area on the left is the RAM used by the 20 Zoekt replicas alone, and the tiny lines under it are all the other jobs. The drops represent deploying the changes described in this post.","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1,"offset":1387},"end":{"line":10,"column":220,"offset":1606},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1,"offset":1387},"end":{"line":10,"column":220,"offset":1606},"indent":[]}},{"type":"html","value":"<img src=\"/blog/ram-usage.png\" width=1200 alt=\"RAM used by the 20 Zoekt replicas\"/>","position":{"start":{"line":12,"column":1,"offset":1608},"end":{"line":12,"column":84,"offset":1691},"indent":[]}},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Here’s how we achieved a 5x reduction in memory usage with no measurable latency changes.","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1,"offset":1693},"end":{"line":14,"column":90,"offset":1782},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1,"offset":1693},"end":{"line":14,"column":90,"offset":1782},"indent":[]}},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"children":[{"type":"link","url":"#Step-1-Measure-how-a-servers-RAM-is-being-used","title":null,"children":[],"data":{"hProperties":{"aria-label":"Step 1 Measure how a servers RAM is being used permalink","class":"anchor before"},"hChildren":[{"type":"raw","value":"<svg aria-hidden=\"true\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" viewBox=\"0 18 95 120\" height=\"18\" width=\"18\"><path d=\"M53.69,78.7H37.94l-5.85,25H21.74l5.85-25H15.89L18,69.1H29.84l4.65-19.65H23.39l2.1-9.6H36.74l5.7-23.7H52.79l-5.7,23.7H62.84l5.7-23.7H78.89l-5.7,23.7H84.74l-2.4,9.6H70.94L66.29,69.1H77.24l-2.4,9.6H64l-5.85,25H47.84Zm-13.5-9.6H55.94l4.65-19.65H44.84Z\"/></svg>"}]}},{"type":"text","value":"Step 1: Measure how a server’s RAM is being used","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":4,"offset":1787},"end":{"line":16,"column":52,"offset":1835},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1,"offset":1784},"end":{"line":16,"column":52,"offset":1835},"indent":[]},"data":{"id":"Step-1-Measure-how-a-servers-RAM-is-being-used","htmlAttributes":{"id":"Step-1-Measure-how-a-servers-RAM-is-being-used"},"hProperties":{"id":"Step-1-Measure-how-a-servers-RAM-is-being-used","style":"position:relative;"}}},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"As a first optimization step, a test corpus was created from one of the Zoekt backend servers, and a memory profile was collected to measure precisely how a server’s RAM was being consumed. The corpus has 19,000 different repos, 2.6 billion lines of code, and takes 166GB on disk. Go has ","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1,"offset":1837},"end":{"line":18,"column":289,"offset":2125},"indent":[]}},{"type":"link","title":null,"url":"https://golang.org/doc/diagnostics#profiling","children":[{"type":"text","value":"built-in profiling tools","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":290,"offset":2126},"end":{"line":18,"column":314,"offset":2150},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":289,"offset":2125},"end":{"line":18,"column":361,"offset":2197},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" with deep runtime integrations that make it easy to collect this information. The memory profile below shows 22GB of live objects on one server. The actual RAM usage of a Go program depends on how aggressive the garbage collector is. By default, it can use roughly twice as much memory as the size of the live objects, but you can set the ","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":361,"offset":2197},"end":{"line":18,"column":701,"offset":2537},"indent":[]}},{"type":"html","value":"<code class=\"language-text\">GOGC</code>","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":701,"offset":2537},"end":{"line":18,"column":707,"offset":2543},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" environment variable to more aggressively reduce the maximum overhead. We run Zoekt with ","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":707,"offset":2543},"end":{"line":18,"column":797,"offset":2633},"indent":[]}},{"type":"html","value":"<code class=\"language-text\">GOGC=50</code>","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":797,"offset":2633},"end":{"line":18,"column":806,"offset":2642},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":" to reduce the likelihood that it will exceed its available memory.","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":806,"offset":2642},"end":{"line":18,"column":873,"offset":2709},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1,"offset":1837},"end":{"line":18,"column":873,"offset":2709},"indent":[]}},{"type":"html","value":"<figure>\n  <img src=\"/blog/22GB of live objects on one server.png\" alt=\"22GB of live objects on one server\" class=\"no-shadow\">\n  <figcaption>22GB of live objects on one server.</figcaption>\n</figure>","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1,"offset":2711},"end":{"line":23,"column":10,"offset":2910},"indent":[1,1,1]}},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The memory profile shows which functions are responsible for allocating RAM, and it’s immediately apparent that readNgrams is responsible for 67% of the memory usage. Digging into ","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1,"offset":2912},"end":{"line":25,"column":181,"offset":3092},"indent":[]}},{"type":"link","title":null,"url":"https://github.com/google/zoekt/blob/d5ee8b074530f291e1173f8e79f7fcdb4d972cc5/read.go#L256","children":[{"type":"text","value":"the code","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":182,"offset":3093},"end":{"line":25,"column":190,"offset":3101},"indent":[]}}],"position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":181,"offset":3092},"end":{"line":25,"column":283,"offset":3194},"indent":[]}},{"type":"text","value":", this turned out to be a function that builds a map from trigrams to the location of a posting list on disk. It